revision.text:
{{for|the journalist|Carlos Manuel Acuña}} {{Infobox person | name = Carlos Acuña | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = Carlos Ernesto di Loreto | birth_date = November 4, 1915 | birth_place = [[Buenos Aires]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1999|2|19|1914|11|3}} | death_place = Buenos Aires | death_cause = | residence = | other_names = | known_for = Tango vocalist | education = | employer = | occupation = Composer and singer | title = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | signature = | website = | nationality = [[Argentine]] }} '''Carlos Acuña''' (November 4, 1915<ref>{{Cite book|title = Anuario del tango|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=EpgNAAAAYAAJ|publisher = Corregidor|date = 1998-01-01|language = es|first = Roberto|last = Cassinelli|first2 = Raúl|last2 = Outeda|page = 350}}</ref> – February 19, 1999<ref>{{Cite web|title = Muere, a los 83 años, el cantante de tangos Carlos Acuña|url = http://elpais.com/diario/1999/02/20/cultura/919465207_850215.html|website = EL PAÍS|date = 1999-02-20|access-date = 2016-02-04|language = es|first = Ediciones El|last = País}}</ref>) was an [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[Tango music|Tango]] singer and composer. As a vocalist, he was best known for his performance of ''La Calesita'' ("The Merry-Go-Round"); and as a composer, for ''Un boliche'' ("A Tavern").<ref name=tango>{{cite web|url=http://www.todotango.com/english/creadores/cacuna.asp|title=Carlos Acuña|author=Jorge Palacio|work=Todo Tango}}</ref>
Born Carlos Ernesto di Loreto, Acuña began his career in the 1930s and became known for his deep and highly expressive voice. He performed with orchestra leaders such as Ernesto de la Cruz, [[Carlos di Sarli]], and [[Mariano Mores]]; the poet and tango lyricist [[Celedonio Flores]], his closest friend, introduced many of his performances until his own death in 1947.<ref name=tango/>
Acuña joined Mores' orchestra in 1955, with whom he recorded 15 albums for [[Odeon Records]]. His foreign travels as a performer brought him success in [[Uruguay]], [[Mexico]], [[Italy]] and [[Spain]], where he became a close friend of the exiled [[Juan Perón]]. He lived in Spain for 17 years, where he obtained great success, then returned to Argentina in 1978.<ref name=tango/>
He died in [[Buenos Aires]] in 1999,<ref name=tango/> and was interred in [[La Chacarita Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/7345452|title=Carlos Acuña|work=Find-a-Grave}}</ref>
