{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = Mira Lesmana | image = Mira lesmana scroundbites 2007.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Mira Lesmana in 2007 | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1964|08|08}} | birth_place =[[Jakarta, Indonesia]] | death_date = <!--{{death date and age|df=yes|1985|07|19|1934|08|5}}--> | death_place = | death_cause = | residence = | nationality = Indonesian | education = | alma_mater = Jakarta Arts Institute | occupation = Producer, director | years_active = | notable_works = {{plainlist | * ''[[Petualangan Sherina]]'' * ''[[Ada Apa dengan Cinta?]]'' * ''[[Gie]]'' * ''[[Laskar Pelangi]]'' }} | style = | spouse = Mathias Muchus <small>(1990-present)</small> | children = 2 | awards = | influences = | influenced = | ethnicity = | religion = }}
'''Mira Lesmana''' (born 8 August 1964) is an Indonesian film director, producer and songwriter. She is best known as the founder of Miles Films, previously Miles Productions, which she co-manages with Indonesian filmmaker [[Riri Riza]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://milesfilms.net/about/|title=Miles Films {{!}} Miles Films|website=milesfilms.net|language=ID|access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref> Through Miles Films, she has produced several critically and commercially successful films, including ''[[Petualangan Sherina]]'' (''Sherina's Adventure''; 2000), ''[[Ada Apa dengan Cinta?]]'' (''What's Up with Love?''; 2002), ''[[Gie]]'' (2005), and ''[[Laskar Pelangi]]'' (''The Rainbow Troops''; 2008).
==Early life== Lesmana was born in Jakarta to musician Jack Lesmana and his wife Nien.{{sfn|Setiawan 2008, Mira Lesmana: Living}}{{sfn|Femina, Mira Lesmana (1)}} Her younger brother is jazz pianist [[Indra Lesmana]].{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2010, Mira creates 20 songs}} At the age of five, she entered kindergarten at Cikini School; her primary and middle school education were conducted at the same institution.{{sfn|Femina, Mira Lesmana (1)}}{{sfn|Femina, Mira Lesmana (2)}} As a child, Lesmana wanted to be either a scientist or detective, and was often at the top of her class.{{sfn|Femina, Mira Lesmana (1)}} She later recalled that seeing [[George Lucas]]' ''[[Star Wars Episode IV: A New Hope]]'' (1977) "blew [her] off [her] feet" and may have inspired her to go into film making.{{sfn|Emond 2008, Mira Lesmana: 'I}}
At the age of 16, Lesmana wrote her first song, which her brother Indra used to gain a scholarship to a music school in Australia. As Indra was still a teenager, the family moved to Australia with him in 1979. Lesmana continued her education there; although she had previously studied English in Indonesia, she found difficulty with the [[Australian accent]].{{sfn|Femina, Mira Lesmana (3)}} She also started watching films regularly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://entertainment.kompas.com/read/2016/05/18/144354710/mira.lesmana.perjalanan.merekam.zaman|title=Mira Lesmana: Perjalanan Merekam Zaman - Kompas.com|last=Media|first=Kompas Cyber|access-date=23 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> After her second year in Australia, Lesmana transferred from a public school to the Australian International Independence School. After her graduation, the Lesmana family returned to Indonesia.{{sfn|Femina, Mira Lesmana (4)}} She enrolled at the Jakarta Art Institute in 1983, graduating in 1985.{{sfn|Miles Productions, Mira Lesmana}} Her first experience with film producing was a [[public service announcement]] made at the request of [[Garin Nugroho]].{{sfn|Siregar 2011, Mira Lesmana: The Fighter}}
On 14 February 1990, Lesmana married former teen idol, actor Mathias Muchus;{{sfn|Femina, Mira Lesmana (6)}} the couple have two sons, Galih Galinggis and Kafka Keandre.{{sfn|Ivvaty 2008, Mira, Muchus}} Throughout the early 1990s Lesmana continued writing songs, including some for her brother{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2010, Mira creates 20 songs}} and one for [[Chrisye]]'s 1993 album ''Sendiri Lagi'' (''Alone Again'').{{sfn|Liner notes for ''Sendiri Lagi''}} In 1995 she established a film production company, Miles Productions, which was later renamed Miles Films.{{sfn|Miles Productions, Mira Lesmana}} In 1996 she directed a successful documentary serial entitled ''Anak Seribu Pulau'' (''Children of a Thousand Islands'').{{sfn|Siregar 2011, Mira Lesmana: The Fighter}}
==Film career== In 1999 Lesmana made her feature film debut with ''Kuldesak'', which she co-directed with Riza Mantovani, [[Riri Riza]] and Nan Triveni.{{sfn|Siregar 2011, Mira Lesmana: The Fighter}} The following year she produced ''[[Petualangan Sherina]]'' (''Sherina's Adventure'').{{sfn|Setiawan 2008, Mira Lesmana: Living}} At the time, the [[Cinema of Indonesia|Indonesian film industry]] was in decline, and several filmmakers ridiculed the efforts, saying that the films could not be profitable; both were nevertheless successful.{{sfn|Emond 2008, Mira Lesmana: 'I}} In 2002 Lesmana released ''[[Ada Apa dengan Cinta?]]'' (''What's Up with Love?''), serving as co-producer with Riza.{{sfn|Miles Productions, Mira Lesmana}} Iwan Setiawan, writing in ''[[The Jakarta Post]]'', describes these films as having jump-started the industry's recovery.{{sfn|Setiawan 2008, Mira Lesmana: Living}}
[[File:Mira Lesmana and Riri Riza.jpg|thumb|left|Mira Lesmana (left) with fellow director and producer [[Riri Riza]] in 2013]] Lesmana produced ''[[Gie]]'', a biopic of activist [[Soe Hok Gie]], in 2005. Although a critical success, it did not break even.{{sfn|Siregar 2011, Mira Lesmana: The Fighter}} The following year Lesmana was a founding member of the Indonesian Film Society ({{lang|id|Masyarakat Film Indonesia}}), which worked to change censorship laws in the country.{{sfn|Setiawan 2008, Mira Lesmana: Living}} The group's petitions were ultimately unsuccessful.{{sfn|Siregar 2011, Mira Lesmana: The Fighter}} Also in 2006 she produced ''Garasi'' (''Garage''), a film starring Aries Budiman, Ayu Ratna, and Fedi Nuril. The cast reunited to form the band Garasi in 2007, which was one of the first acts signed to Lesmana's new recording company Miles Music. That year she produced ''[[3 Hari Untuk Selamanya]]'' (''3 Days for Forever''); the film's soundtrack was produced by Float, another band on Miles Music.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2008, Mira follows in family}}
In 2008 Lesmana produced the film ''[[Laskar Pelangi]]'' (''Rainbow Troops''), an adaptation of [[Andrea Hirata]]'s 2007 novel of the same name.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2010, Mira creates 20 songs}} That same year she continued to pressure for new film censorship laws, which ended with the government passing a new law in 2009.{{sfn|Siregar 2011, Mira Lesmana: The Fighter}} The following year she produced ''Sang Pemimpi'' (''The Dreamer''), a sequel to ''Laskar Pelangi'' based on the novel of the same name.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009, 'The Dreamer' brings}} In 2010 Lesmana wrote twenty songs for a musical stage adaptation of ''Laskar Pelangi'', a project that also involved [[Erwin Gutawa]], Jay Subiyakto, and Hartandi.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2010, Mira creates 20 songs}}
''Atambua 39° Celsius'', a film about refugees who live in [[Atambua]], commenced filming in 2012.{{sfn|Siregar 2012, Ordinary People the Stars of New Film Set in NTT Village}} The film was partially funded through crowd-funding and had its world premiere at the Tokyo International Film Festival.{{sfn|ANTARA News 2012, 'Atambua 39 Derajat Celcius' Tokyo International Film Festival}} The following year, she released ''Sokola Rimba'' which won Best Film at the Maya Awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gatra.com/entertainmen/film-1/44296-sokola-rimba-raih-film-terpilih-piala-maya-2013.html|title=Gatranews - ''Sokola Rimba'' Raih Film Terpilih Piala Maya 2013|access-date=23 March 2017|language=en-gb}}</ref>
Lesmana’s most expensive production {{as of|2017|lc=yes}} to date was ''Pendekar Tongkat Emas'' (''[[The Golden Cane Warrior]]''; 2014), a martial arts film directed by [[Ifa Isfansyah]]. Starring Eva Celia, [[Nicholas Saputra]], and [[Reza Rahadian]], it had an estimated budget of 25 billion rupiah.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://movienthusiast.com/budget-pendekar-tongkat-emas-telan-angka-fantastis/|title=Budget "Pendekar Tongkat Emas" Telan Angka Fantastis! {{!}} Movienthusiast.com|website=movienthusiast.com|language=en-US|access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref>
In 2016, Lesmana produced ''[[Ada Apa Dengan Cinta? 2|Ada Apa dengan Cinta? 2]]'' (''What's Up with Love? 2'';), a sequel to ''Ada Apa dengan Cinta''. Like its predecessor, the film was a hit with audiences, and as of June 2016 had been watched by more than 3.6 million people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tribunnews.com/seleb/2016/06/01/36-juta-penonton-antarkan-ada-apa-dengan-cinta-2-ke-puncak-box-office-indonesia|title=3,6 Juta Penonton Antarkan Ada Apa dengan Cinta 2? ke Puncak Box Office Indonesia - Tribunnews.com|work=Tribunnews.com|access-date=23 March 2017|language=id-ID}}</ref> Also in the same year, Lesmana released ''Athirah'' (''Emma' (Mother)''), a film inspired by the life of Indonesian Vice President [[Jusuf Kalla]]’s mother.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.tempo.co/read/news/2016/08/23/109797967/athirah-kisah-ibunda-jk-diangkat-ke-novel-dan-film|title=Athirah, Kisah Ibunda JK Diangkat ke Novel dan Film|last=Tempo.Co|work=Tempo News|access-date=23 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The film won both the [[Indonesian Film Festival|Citra Award]] and Maya Award for Best Film and had been screened at several international film festivals to positive reviews.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.tempo.co/read/news/2016/11/07/111818200/ffi-2016-athirah-boyong-enam-piala-citra|title=FFI 2016, 'Athirah' Boyong Enam Piala Citra|last=Tempo.Co|work=Tempo News|access-date=23 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnnindonesia.com/hiburan/20161219085004-220-180606/dominasi-athirah-dan-daftar-pemenang-piala-maya-2016/|title=Dominasi Athirah dan Daftar Pemenang Piala Maya 2016|work=CNN Indonesia|access-date=23 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/life/2017/02/16/athirah-wins-award-at-french-film-festival.html|title=‘Athirah’ wins award at French film festival|last=Post|first=The Jakarta|work=The Jakarta Post|access-date=23 March 2017|language=en}}</ref>
